1
00:00:01,200 --> 00:00:02,060
Hi everyone.

2
00:00:02,820 --> 00:00:08,580
I equipped this lazy converter build with voltage feedback.

3
00:00:09,200 --> 00:00:13,140
Now it stably holds 238 V at the output.

4
00:00:14,440 --> 00:00:17,720
The feedback is also done quite simply.

5
00:00:17,880 --> 00:00:19,800
Two additional chips.

6
00:00:20,540 --> 00:00:27,500
One of them is a PC817 optocoupler, the other a TL431 adjustable shunt regulator.

7
00:00:28,700 --> 00:00:32,240
4 resistors, 1 capacitor.

8
00:00:32,360 --> 00:00:34,380
That's the whole feedback.

9
00:00:35,040 --> 00:00:43,280
So this converter now lets you supply not only 12 V at the input but also up to 20 V inclusive.

10
00:00:43,960 --> 00:00:48,900
In any voltage range of that order.

11
00:00:49,580 --> 00:00:52,840
And the output voltage is stabilized.

12
00:00:53,720 --> 00:01:00,940
Now we'll test it and look at the feedback circuit in more detail.

13
00:01:01,700 --> 00:01:06,320
Now we'll test the voltage feedback trip point.

14
00:01:06,880 --> 00:01:11,340
A multimeter is connected to the output — the lamp isn't connected.

15
00:01:12,460 --> 00:01:14,560
Applying 12 V power.

16
00:01:16,300 --> 00:01:22,320
You can hear the converter trip point — it starts to buzz.

17
00:01:23,920 --> 00:01:26,000
That's the sound.

18
00:01:26,960 --> 00:01:28,140
237 V.

19
00:01:30,560 --> 00:01:32,060
Connect the lamp.

20
00:01:32,820 --> 00:01:36,760
You see there's a slight drop on the lamp — 218 V.

21
00:01:37,240 --> 00:01:45,100
The output voltage went away from the feedback trip point and the converter runs in normal mode.

22
00:01:45,740 --> 00:01:46,920
No sound at all.

23
00:01:49,360 --> 00:01:56,420
With voltage feedback present, we can supply a higher voltage at the input.

24
00:01:57,240 --> 00:02:00,920
Up to 20 V — not worth going higher.

25
00:02:01,820 --> 00:02:04,420
Now applying 14 V.

26
00:02:06,020 --> 00:02:15,020
You see the voltage is within norm and the feedback trip sound appeared.

27
00:02:15,460 --> 00:02:24,260
The sound comes from the step-up transformer, since the chip now drives the switches in pulse bursts mode.

28
00:02:27,930 --> 00:02:31,850
If we reduce, the sound disappears.

29
00:02:31,950 --> 00:02:33,910
Feedback fully works.

30
00:02:34,350 --> 00:02:37,930
About what you can connect to this converter.

31
00:02:39,130 --> 00:02:51,130
You can connect all modern devices that have a transformerless inverter at the input.

32
00:02:51,250 --> 00:03:00,230
That is, mobile phone chargers, laptop chargers, and similar devices.

33
00:03:00,570 --> 00:03:07,470
You can't connect devices that have a step-down transformer at the input.

34
00:03:07,930 --> 00:03:17,550
Such power supplies — their weight is significantly higher than an inverter-type supply.

35
00:03:17,970 --> 00:03:22,210
You also can't connect asynchronous motors here.

36
00:03:22,570 --> 00:03:27,770
Most often we encounter them in everyday life in fans, for example.

37
00:03:29,010 --> 00:03:34,790
And brushed motors that are here will work freely.

38
00:03:34,790 --> 00:03:46,390
That is, various kinds of small drills at 220 V, with power up to 200 W — this system will freely power them.

39
00:03:47,570 --> 00:03:56,150
To add voltage feedback to our circuit, we use a property of the IR2153 chip.

40
00:03:56,950 --> 00:04:06,630
If you apply logical zero to pin 3 of this chip, the chip stops generating on both channels.

41
00:04:07,470 --> 00:04:17,550
For this I went with a variant using a galvanically isolated optocoupler — the widespread PC817.

42
00:04:19,850 --> 00:04:26,390
I soldered it into the circuit per its pinout.

43
00:04:27,110 --> 00:04:33,910
Pins 1 and 2 are the infrared LED built into the optocoupler.

44
00:04:34,730 --> 00:04:38,690
Pins 3 and 4 are the phototransistor.

45
00:04:39,770 --> 00:04:49,370
The optocoupler is this small part — here it is — with four pins.

46
00:04:50,770 --> 00:05:01,430
On the top of the case there's a dot, which marks pin numbering.

47
00:05:01,550 --> 00:05:02,390
This is pin 1.

48
00:05:02,870 --> 00:05:11,610
The pins, if you look starting from the dot — in this case it's now at the upper-left corner — are counted counter-clockwise.

49
00:05:11,730 --> 00:05:14,870
First, second, third, and fourth.

50
00:05:15,530 --> 00:05:21,930
On the schematic the optocoupler is shown lying with legs up.

51
00:05:22,930 --> 00:05:26,110
That orientation matches its pinout.

52
00:05:26,950 --> 00:05:30,270
So, solder the optocoupler into the circuit.

53
00:05:31,530 --> 00:05:35,090
Here you can see I installed it on the board.

54
00:05:35,430 --> 00:05:38,470
And check whether the optocoupler works.

55
00:05:39,390 --> 00:05:50,070
For this we apply power to the converter, first soldering a small load to it.

56
00:05:50,350 --> 00:05:54,230
In this case a 15 W lamp.

57
00:05:55,470 --> 00:05:57,430
Apply power.

58
00:06:00,310 --> 00:06:03,150
You see, the lamp lit.

59
00:06:03,970 --> 00:06:11,430
Now we need to solder a wire to pin 2 of the optocoupler.

60
00:06:12,050 --> 00:06:12,210
There it is.

61
00:06:13,230 --> 00:06:19,050
And to pin 1 of the optocoupler — a 91 Ω current-limiting resistor.

62
00:06:19,750 --> 00:06:21,710
And a 1.5 V battery.

63
00:06:22,630 --> 00:06:26,130
Minus from the battery goes to pin 2.

64
00:06:26,790 --> 00:06:28,690
Plus to the resistor.

65
00:06:29,590 --> 00:06:31,990
And watch — I connect the battery.

66
00:06:35,070 --> 00:06:44,830
And when the battery plus is connected to the resistor, the chip stops generation, the load goes out.

67
00:06:46,970 --> 00:06:52,970
This experiment shows the optocoupler is in working order.

68
00:06:53,790 --> 00:07:10,930
If you have a lab signal generator on hand, you can watch how the converter triggers under optocoupler control with a square signal applied to the input — the generator common

69
00:07:10,930 --> 00:07:18,690
connects to pin 2, the signal one to pin 1, also through a current-limiting resistor.

70
00:07:20,590 --> 00:07:24,150
The input potential should be no more than 5 V.

71
00:07:24,330 --> 00:07:29,810
1.5-2 V is enough to trigger the optocoupler easily.

72
00:07:30,130 --> 00:07:32,510
Equivalent to what we did with the battery.

73
00:07:32,770 --> 00:07:38,250
I'm applying a square signal at 10 Hz.

74
00:07:39,310 --> 00:07:44,710
You see the circuit responds great.

75
00:07:45,270 --> 00:07:46,510
Reducing frequency.

76
00:07:47,650 --> 00:07:49,030
5 Hz.

77
00:07:50,130 --> 00:08:02,850
Understand — those who work with electronics — on this principle you can already form chip operation in burst mode.

78
00:08:05,390 --> 00:08:06,710
1 Hz frequency.

79
00:08:09,410 --> 00:08:16,750
If you apply, say, mains frequency — here I smoothly raise it, now 25 Hz.

80
00:08:21,390 --> 00:08:22,350
50.

81
00:08:22,610 --> 00:08:32,430
You can hear — when there'll be a way to supply this — that this step-up transformer hums at 50 Hz mains frequency.

82
00:08:33,690 --> 00:08:38,270
Next, we need to introduce another element into the circuit.

83
00:08:38,390 --> 00:08:41,050
The TL431 chip.

84
00:08:42,390 --> 00:08:44,810
Graphically it's shown as a zener.

85
00:08:44,970 --> 00:08:49,210
With a branch you get an adjustable shunt regulator system.

86
00:08:50,310 --> 00:08:54,390
The pinout is shown under the graphic.

87
00:08:55,130 --> 00:08:59,370
The part itself is also very small.

88
00:08:59,890 --> 00:09:00,330
Here it is.

89
00:09:02,150 --> 00:09:03,510
Three pins on the part.

90
00:09:04,250 --> 00:09:13,870
Pins are counted left to right if you read the chip name straight-on.

91
00:09:15,350 --> 00:09:16,810
What's this for?

92
00:09:17,830 --> 00:09:36,570
Earlier I shared a schematic of another converter, and you can see that here, by feedback, the master chip is controlled directly through the PC817 optocoupler by dividing

93
00:09:36,570 --> 00:09:43,230
voltage on a series resistor stack.

94
00:09:44,050 --> 00:10:03,650
You can't control it that way in this circuit, because if the LED's glow has different intensity, the phototransistor — since it's bipolar — will open with different conductivity levels.

95
00:09:36,570 --> 00:10:07,590
Open with various degrees of conductivity.

96
00:10:08,490 --> 00:10:15,810
And if you measure it, play with the optocoupler, you'll see the transistor's resistance changes.

97
00:10:16,350 --> 00:10:28,610
And for this chip you need at least 200 Ω of resistance to reliably short pin 3 to the common wire.

98
00:10:29,330 --> 00:10:39,610
That's exactly why an additional sensitive element — the TL431 — was added, which controls this optocoupler.

99
00:10:40,590 --> 00:10:46,450
The TL431 is a pretty elderly chip for us.

100
00:10:47,410 --> 00:10:55,210
Made in the late 1970s, but still widely used to this day.

101
00:10:56,390 --> 00:11:08,930
Its advantages are operating voltage up to 36 V and the main one — being able to set the chip's trip points.

102
00:11:09,850 --> 00:11:19,650
Inside there's a reference power source of about 2.5 V and a comparator.

103
00:11:19,850 --> 00:11:32,010
The comparator has stabilized 2.5 V at one input, and the input from the external part, pin 1, at the other.

104
00:11:32,530 --> 00:11:36,650
The comparator compares the reference and the input voltage.

105
00:11:36,710 --> 00:11:48,570
If the input exceeds the reference, the chip triggers and, graphically speaking, the zener "breaks down" — i.e. the chip starts to conduct.

106
00:11:49,450 --> 00:11:52,830
I picked the divider on the resistors.

107
00:11:52,850 --> 00:11:58,090
1-watt resistors of 4.6 kΩ and 390 kΩ.

108
00:11:58,530 --> 00:12:15,870
With these resistor values, if you take its leads already from the converter output, the voltage protection trips at 238 V.

109
00:12:17,110 --> 00:12:27,690
That is, by changing the values of the 4.6 kΩ resistor, you can set the converter's trip point.

110
00:12:28,690 --> 00:12:37,570
You mustn't forget to put this capacitor of at least 10 nF, ceramic, between pins 3 and 1.

111
00:12:38,090 --> 00:12:46,190
Otherwise false feedback triggers are possible from some transient processes in the transformer.

112
00:12:46,270 --> 00:12:54,950
For example, if there are needle-like voltage spikes, the chip will trigger earlier than needed.

113
00:12:55,230 --> 00:12:56,690
Capacitor is mandatory.

114
00:12:57,830 --> 00:13:06,030
And this 1 kΩ resistor placed in parallel with the optocoupler's LED.

115
00:13:06,610 --> 00:13:21,510
This resistor also keeps the LED from glowing when the TL431 chip is approaching its trip point.

116
00:13:22,790 --> 00:13:26,250
Limiting resistor 150 Ω.

117
00:13:27,410 --> 00:13:34,570
I searched for feedbacks of this kind online at first, but interestingly, found nothing.

118
00:13:34,710 --> 00:13:42,670
Lots of such solutions for low voltage, but with high voltage I had to fiddle.

119
00:13:45,690 --> 00:13:54,810
I picked the divider through long practice and changed various circuit variants until it started working stably.

120
00:13:56,650 --> 00:14:10,250
Many parts for this converter can be borrowed from broken power supplies — for example, from computer power supplies.

121
00:14:11,930 --> 00:14:18,990
You can buy them cheap or you may be given them for free at service centers.

122
00:14:20,570 --> 00:14:29,950
In particular, you can see on the board there's a PC817 optocoupler and this chip.

123
00:14:32,270 --> 00:14:34,650
A small TL431.

124
00:14:37,050 --> 00:14:40,850
Also heat sinks you can mount transistors on.

125
00:14:43,270 --> 00:14:48,270
Thermal insulating gaskets under these transistors — you can find them all here.

126
00:14:50,210 --> 00:14:53,010
And this is also quite suitable.

127
00:14:54,130 --> 00:14:57,150
You can disassemble this transformer.

128
00:14:58,430 --> 00:15:17,290
I unsoldered it from the board, but usually either heat it with a heat gun until the glue melts and the halves separate, or boil it in water until it falls apart.

129
00:15:17,410 --> 00:15:26,290
After this it's all unwound, and you wind your own winding to the voltages you want.

130
00:15:26,790 --> 00:15:33,850
So this converter can be very cheap if you make it from salvage.

131
00:15:36,450 --> 00:15:55,250
If this converter will be used, for example, for lighting when power is out, then I'd suggest in this case putting some 20 A diode at the input — any brand,

132
00:15:55,450 --> 00:15:58,430
whatever you find.

133
00:15:59,210 --> 00:16:02,450
Voltage rating not less than 100 V.

134
00:16:04,770 --> 00:16:12,530
So in poor lighting conditions you don't mix up the power inputs.

135
00:16:12,670 --> 00:16:23,430
Otherwise, if you mix them up, the circuit will of course go bad immediately, the chip will fail, and possibly one of the switches will blow.

136
00:16:24,810 --> 00:16:30,550
If it's stationary and constantly connected, you can skip the diode.

137
00:16:31,470 --> 00:16:37,430
But anyone who wants can also equip the input with a fuse.

138
00:16:40,010 --> 00:16:43,530
That is, at your discretion you can upgrade this circuit.

139
00:16:43,530 --> 00:16:49,610
Also on this principle — I applied this feedback by voltage.

140
00:16:49,870 --> 00:17:04,210
I need an operating voltage point such that... if voltage feedback is built, you can supply not just 12 V but up to 20 V inclusive at the input, and with that it'll

141
00:17:04,210 --> 00:17:07,030
stably hold output voltage.

142
00:17:07,150 --> 00:17:14,910
You can even pocket two 9V (Krona-type) batteries, connect them in series, and supply 18 V at the input.

143
00:17:15,750 --> 00:17:20,570
And you'll have 220 V at the output.

144
00:17:20,570 --> 00:17:23,510
Always able to charge your phone.

145
00:17:26,870 --> 00:17:29,190
The whole circuit is that flexible.

146
00:17:31,490 --> 00:17:37,110
Anyone interested can also assemble current feedback.

147
00:17:37,190 --> 00:17:43,730
That is, if you want the chip to go into protection on output shorting.

148
00:17:43,830 --> 00:17:58,730
For this you'll need to change the divider resistor, wind a small toroidal transformer — the so-called current transformer.

149
00:17:58,810 --> 00:18:09,390
You can hang it at this common point with the power plus to the center of the primary winding.

150
00:18:10,070 --> 00:18:22,630
And by playing with its turn count, bring the operating voltage point to somewhere above 2.6 V.

151
00:18:23,010 --> 00:18:30,310
Say if this converter works on a 200 V load.

152
00:18:31,130 --> 00:18:40,090
And feed this output from the current sensor to a small diode bridge.

153
00:18:40,430 --> 00:18:42,090
After this put a cap.

154
00:18:43,230 --> 00:18:49,190
Approximately you'll have a circuit analogous to this one shown.

155
00:18:49,230 --> 00:19:06,950
A diode bridge, a cap, and you can end up with a quite working system that protects the converter from short voltage — that is, from a short circuit at its output.

156
00:19:08,420 --> 00:19:12,070
Good luck to everyone with your experiments — all the best!
